</div><div id="accommodations-modal" class="modal fade" role="dialog" aria-hidden="true" style="display: none;"><a aria-label="Dismiss the modal" class="modal-close" data-dismiss="modal" role="button" tabindex="0">\'d7</a>\
<div class="modal-inner">\
  <div class="modal-header">\
    <h1 class="title">\
      <strong>MCAT Official Prep Hub - Accommodations</strong>\
    </h1>\
  </div>\
  <div class="body">\
    <div>\
      <strong>\
        Practicing with Accommodations\
      </strong>\
    </div>\
    \
      <p> If you are approved to take the MCAT exam with accommodations, you may wish to practice with accommodations in the MCAT Official Prep Hub. The option to extend the timing for full-length exams can be found on your practice product dashboard. After you select \'93Configure &amp; Start Test,\'94 select \'93Customize Test Options\'94 to choose your extended time. ZoomText is compatible with the MCAT Official Prep Hub. The ability to zoom in and out on your screen is available as a browser function that does not require an approved accommodation.    </p>\
    \
    <p>\
    Learn more about\
    <a href="https://students-residents.aamc.org/mcat-exam-accommodations/take-mcat-exam-accommodations" target="_blank"> testing with accommodations. </a>\
    </p>\
  </div>\
</div>\
</div><div id="interpret-results-modal" class="interpret-results-modal modal fade" role="dialog" aria-hidden="true" style="display: none;"><a aria-label="Dismiss the modal" class="modal-close" data-dismiss="modal" role="button" tabindex="0">\'d7</a>\
<div class="modal-inner">\
  <div class="modal-header">\
    <h1 class="title">\
      <strong>Interpreting My Results</strong>\
    </h1>\
  </div>\
  <div class="modal-body">\
    \
      <p>\
        Analysis shows that AAMC MCAT Official Practice Exam scores provide a reliable indicator of how examinees will perform on test day. Scores on the official exam typically align closely with examinees most recent practice exam performance \'96 both for total scores and section scores.\
      </p>\
      <p>\
        Some natural variation between practice and official scores is normal and expected. Factors that can influence performance differences include time elapsed between the practice exam and real exam, different testing environments (home vs. test center), recent exposure to specific content areas, and differences in focus and concentration.\
      </p>\
      <p>\
        To get the most accurate prediction from practice tests, examinees should take practice tests under conditions that mirror the actual exam, maintain consistent preparation between practice test and test day, consider their most recent practice test scores as the best indicator, and account for normal day-to-day performance variation.\
      </p>\
    \
    \
      <span class="header underlined">Scoring Information</span>\
      <p>\
        Practice exams are scored on the same scale as the actual MCAT exam.\
      </p>\
      <span class="header underlined">Scaled Scores</span>\
      <p>\
        You will receive a separate scaled Scores for each of the four sections of the MCAT exam, as well as a total score. Each section is scored from a low of 118 to a high of 132. Your total score is the sum of the four individual section scores and will range from 472 to 528. There is no penalty for guessing on the MCAT exam or on MCAT Official Prep practice exams.\
      </p>\
      <span class="header underlined">Percentile Ranks</span>\
      <p>\
        The percentile ranks provided on your Score Reports are the same ones used for the actual MCAT exam. They show the percentages of examinees on the actual MCAT exam who received the same or lower score on the exam than your practice exam score. They show how your scores compare to the scores of everyone who sat for the actual MCAT exam. Every year on May 1, the percentile ranks are updated using data from the most recent three years. The percentile rank shown in your Score Report reflects the percentile rank in use when you began the attempt of the practice exam. For example, if you began an attempt on a practice exam in April 2025, your Score Report reflects the percentile rank updated in May 2024. If you begin a practice exam in June 2025, your percentile rank will reflect the new percentile rank, updated in May 2025. <a href="https://students-residents.aamc.org/mcat-research-and-data/percentile-ranks-mcat-exam" target="_blank">See a more detailed description of MCAT percentile ranks.<span class="sr-only">This opens a new tab</span></a>\
      </p>\
    \
    \
      <span class="header underlined">Reviewing Results</span>\
      <p>\
        \
          The Question Review screen allows you to understand each question and view the solution. The Content and Skills Breakdown section allows you to see how you performed in each foundational concept, content category, skill, and discipline. The higher the number of questions taken in a given content and skill area, the more reflective it is of your performance in that area. Learn more about the content and skills tested by seeing how questions are categorized in the <a href="https://students-residents.aamc.org/prepare-mcat-exam/whats-mcat-exam" target="_blank">What\'92s on the MCAT Exam? Content Outline. <span class="sr-only">Opens in new window</span></a>\
        \
      </p>\
    \
  </div>\
